This paper deals with game theory and decision-making, which are central topics in computer science. The paper specifically focuses on the value of information in noncooperative games, which falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also uses numerical simulations and discusses the implications of the results, which suggests that it may fall under the categories of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper uses mathematical analysis to prove its results, which suggests that it may also fall under the categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
